Roasty Toasty Pecan-Caramel Shortbread Cookies

95% Would Make Again
March 2020
Facebook
Pinterest
Twitter
Email
Makes about 24

The deep, nutty flavor of these tender, buttery shortbread (the fourth recipe in the Basically Guide to Better Baking!) comes from pulverized pecans and store-bought dulce de leche, a confection of sweetened milk cooked down until it's the consistency of caramel sauce. You can find it in a can, near the evaporated and sweetened condensed milks, or in a jar, near the jams. We love the contrasting look of white nonpareil, but feel free to roll the dough in raw sugar or in whatever sprinkles you please. Questions about the recipe? Head to our baking forum and receive a response from one of us or a fellow baker. 

Ingredients

Steps

  1. Place racks in upper and lower thirds of oven (or in middle of oven if you have only 1 baking sheet); preheat to 325°. Toast ⅓ cup (47 g) pecans on a rimmed baking sheet (on the upper or middle rack), tossing halfway through, until fragrant and golden all the way through (check by breaking one in half), 10–12 minutes. Transfer to a food processor; let cool. Reserve baking sheet. Keep the oven at 325° for baking the cookies.

  2. Pulse pecans until very finely ground (be careful not to go too far or you’ll have nut butter). Add 1½ cups plus 2 Tbsp. (188 g) all-purpose flour, 3 Tbsp. sugar, and ½ tsp. kosher salt; pulse once or twice just to combine, scraping down sides as needed.

    Slide 1 of 2

  3. (PAUSE: Is your butter cold? It should be straight-from-the-fridge cold.) Cut 1 cup (2 sticks) chilled unsalted butter into ½" pieces, add to food processor, and pulse in 3-second-long bursts, scraping down sides as needed, until dough begins to come together in large clumps. Add ¼ cup store-bought dulce de leche and pulse until dough comes together into a single mass and no streaks remain.

    Slide 1 of 2

  4. Transfer dough to a sheet of parchment paper (plastic wrap also works here) and use your fingers to pat it down into a rectangle. Don't worry if it's a bit sticky—it's going to firm up when you chill it—but if you're having trouble, lightly flour your fingers. If the dough is still too sticky to work with, transfer it to the fridge for 10 minutes, or until firm enough to handle. Fold parchment up and over dough and use it to press and roll the dough into a 9" log (about 2" in diameter). A bench scraper will help you shape the dough into a straight, even log, but if you don't have one your hands will work just fine. Roll up tightly and chill 90 minutes, or freeze 20 minutes.

  5. Mix remaining 1 Tbsp. store-bought dulce de leche and 2 tsp. water in a small bowl; it should be a pourable consistency.

  6. Spread an even layer of white nonpareil or raw sugar on reserved baking sheet.

  7. Using a pastry brush, very lightly brush outside of chilled dough with the thinned dulce de leche (this will help the sprinkles to adhere).

  8. Roll log in sprinkles, pressing gently to help them stick, until evenly coated. Transfer log to a cutting board. Discard remaining sprinkles or save for another use; line 2 baking sheets with parchment paper (or just 1 if that’s what you’ve got).

  9. Slice dough into ¼"-thick rounds with a sharp chef's knife, rotating log about a quarter of a turn after every 3 or 4 slices to ensure that all of the slices have a nice round shape.

  10. Place cookies on prepared baking sheets, spacing 1" apart (if you have 1 only baking sheet, do this in batches, making sure to let the sheet cool between batches—running it under cold water will speed up the process). Freeze 30 minutes so dough can firm back up (this helps the cookies hold their shape when baked).

  11. Bake cookies, rotating baking sheets top to bottom and front to back halfway through (or just front to back if using 1 baking sheet), until golden brown around the edges, 20–24 minutes. Let cookies set up slightly on baking sheet, then transfer to a wire rack to cool completely (cookies will firm up and get crispier as they cool).

  12. Do ahead: Log of dough can be made 2 days ahead. Keep chilled.

Recipe by Molly Baz
Reviews Section

Reviews

Write a review…
This cookie recipe has earned a spot in my permanent rotation. They crumble beautifully and melt like butter in the mouth. I recommend making the dough recipe as is, and be sure to use a scale and the weight measure for your flour to ensure the right texture. I don't care for nonpareils, and so rolled the dough in finely chopped pecans. I found this to have the added benefit of further balancing the cookie's sweetness. Because they were so popular, I have repeated the recipe a second time, replacing the pecans in the dough and around the edge with lightly salted pistachios. Those turned out well too, and are particularly beautiful! For those in possession of all ingredients except the dulce de leche: it's very easy to make your own with a pot of water, a can of sweetened condensed milk, and patience.

AnonymousMilwaukee, WI03/15/20
I baked these today and thought they were pretty good, but I definitely would do a few things differently if I baked them again. This recipe looks like a bit of a riff on the gone-viral " Salted Butter/Choc. chip shortbread" cookie recipe by Alison Roman, which is now my only go-to for shortbread. I've done lots of different add-ons/flavors but the cold butter was a game changer for shortbread. This recipe also uses cold butter and asks you to brush your dough roll with something and then roll it in something. For Roman's recipe this works beautifully, but to me in this recipe it's a mess. If I were to make them again I'd just cut the cookies, place them on baking sheets, brush the whole top with the thinned dulce de leche, and sprinkle demerara on top. Brushing and rolling meant only the sides had a thin, almost inperceptable bit of sauce and sugar. Like another reviewer, mine spread way more than expected and they were very cold when I baked them. They were hard to get off the parchment even after cooling and crumbled apart. I ended up doing something pretty decadent with them, though, to take them to another level: spread remaining dulce de leche on bottom of one and top with another to make a sandwich cookie. Oh, yeah.
Anonymouswisconsin03/14/20
Loved these! Buttery, crunchy, toasty, and sweet! I used raw sugar to roll and it added just the right touch of sweetness.
NWGregFlorida03/14/20
These cookies are great! I didn't spend enough time making a good round log so the shape was a bit oblong, but that's on me. I, too, used raw sugar on the outside and loved the crunch it gave. Something else I tried and really enjoyed was spreading a little bit of the leftover dulce de leche on each cookie and then topping with flaky salt and some finely crushed pecans. Putting the pecan on top helped reinforce the pecan flavor that I think is pretty subtle in the cookie. Would make again!

Make these as written. Yes, the dough is sticky, but flouring your fingers and using the parchment paper/bench scraper really works. They are delicious and many more batches will be made in this house! For the person asking about using other nuts, you could certainly use any nut you like. Peanuts, almonds, walnuts, cashews, hazelnuts,..... I forgot the step of freezing for 30 minutes before baking, but they held their shape nicely enough - I didn't end up with one big cookie as another reviewer did. I had some leftover finely ground pecans and mixed them with demara sugar for the edge. I don't think you need dulce de leche in particular - any good quality, thick caramel would be great.
